AB  - Abstract. This article analyzes social effects of nearly three decades of post-Soviet reforms in Russia on lite basis of data from a nationwide public opinion monitoring program that spanned the period from 2014 to 2018 and comprised nine sets of surveys. The study addresses the income stratification of post-reform Russian society and compares it with stratification in other countries. It evaluates the living standards and the quality of life of various social groups on the basis of objective wellbeing (OWBJ and subjective wcllbcing (SWB) criteria. The SWB analysis examines respondents' degrees of satisfaction with various aspects of their everyday life and their typical psychoemotional reactions to various social situations. Another subject raised in the article is social mobility in Russia from the late 1980s to this day. The author finishes his article with a set of postulates summarizing the study and with a conclusion that it is not the scale but the quality of state participation in economic, social and cultural affairs that matters in today's Russia.
